"{\"uid\": \"pbs.org-video-battle-style-dance-known-as-breaking-joins-the-2024-paris-olympics-d84dps\", \"text\": \"Clip: Season 51 | 1m 19sVideo hasClosed Captions|CC  Here are three moves in breaking, the newest Olympic sport, that appear to defy the laws of physics.  The 2024 Olympics in Paris debuted a new sport: breaking (also known as breakdancing, but do not call it that). Here are three moves that appear to defy the laws of physics, and how they work.  01/17/2025  Problems playing video?Report a Problem|Closed Captioning Feedback  Before you submit an error, please consult ourVideo Help page.  Problems playing video?Report a Problem|Closed Captioning Feedback  Before you submit an error, please consult ourVideo Help page.  National Corporate funding for NOVA is provided byCarlisle CompaniesandViking Cruises. Major funding for NOVA is provided by the NOVA Science Trust and PBS viewers.  Support provided by:  Clip: Season 51 | 1m 19sVideo hasClosed Captions|CC  The 2024 Olympics in Paris debuted a new sport: breaking (also known as breakdancing, but do not call it that). Here are three moves that appear to defy the laws of physics, and how they work.  01/17/2025  Problems playing video?Report a Problem|Closed Captioning Feedback  Before you submit an error, please consult ourVideo Help page.  #novapbs  NOVA  S51Ep0  NOVAis available to stream on pbs.org and the free PBS App, available on iPhone, Apple TV, Android TV, Android smartphones, Amazon Fire TV, Amazon Fire Tablet, Roku, Samsung Smart TV, and Vizio.  - The 2024 Olympics in Paris is debuting a new sport, breaking, also known as break dancing.  But do not call it that.  Breaking is a battle style of dance that started in the 70s in the Bronx, New York, where breakers freestyle acrobatics and complex footwork to a beat.  Here are three kinds of moves that appear to defy the laws of physics.  Spins are power moves in a breaker's arsenal, where they balance on either their hands, even their heads.  The magic in this move is how the breaker generates and controls their speed with their legs.  Kind of like how a figure skater speeds up when they move their arms in closer.  In physics, this is called conservation of angular momentum.  Floats are another kind of power move that has a ton of variations.  For this move, the breaker uses their arms to seemingly float off the floor.  This requires a ton of core strength.  You thought planks were hard?  And a good sense of knowing where their center of gravity is, or where their weight is evenly distributed.  And then there are freezes, which is when a breaker holds a move or shape with their body for a few seconds.  It's usually used to hit a beat in the music or to signify the end of the sequence.  As you can imagine, holding a pose like this one requires a lot of balance.  This is called static equilibrium, meaning that all the forces on the front, back, left, and right are equal.  See how many of these moves you can catch when you watch the Olympics.  (soft upbeat music)  The Physics of Breaking, a New Olympic Sport  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 1m 19s | Here are three moves in breaking, the newest Olympic sport, that appear to defy the laws of physics. (1m 19s)  What Happens to Your Body During a Speed Eating Competition?  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 5m 16s | Competitive eaters stretch their stomachs beyond limits. Here's what happens inside their bodies. (5m 16s)  Flight Turbulence Is Actually Getting Worse  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 1m 48s | It's not all in your head - flights really are bumpier these days. (1m 48s)  Sir Arthur C. Clarke's Vision of the Computer-Dominated Future  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 1m 39s | Watch this interview with Sir Arthur C. Clarke for The Mind Machine (1978.) (1m 39s)  How Medieval Armorers Made Knights Bulletproof  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 2m 15s | Knights and firearms clashed on the battlefield for over 200 years. (2m 15s)  How Do Hurricanes Form?  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 1m 2s | Hurricanes are getting more intense, faster. (1m 2s)  This Powerful Psychedelic May Help Treat Opioid Addiction  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 3m 28s | In recent decades, there is been renewed interest in studying ibogaine. (3m 28s)  Can Technology Detect Deepfakes Better Than Humans Can?  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 7m 9s | AI-generated photos are video are getting so good that it's hard for humans to tell what's real. (7m 9s)  What Happened to the Hole in the Ozone Layer?  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 3m 13s | In the 1980s scientists discovered a crucial part of the Earth's atmosphere was extremely thin. (3m 13s)  A Hidden Cause of Sinkholes Is Lurking Underground  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 2m 21s | About 40% of the U.S. is susceptible to sinkholes. (2m 21s)  Ozempic's Surprising Real Power  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 3m 51s | Blockbuster drug Ozempic keeps surprising scientists. (3m 51s)  What Dating Apps Know About You  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 2m 51s | You might be collecting matches, but dating apps are collecting your data. (2m 51s)  These cheeses are at risk of going extinct  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 1m 11s | The culprit is a lack of microbial biodiversity in the mold used to make iconic French cheeses. (1m 11s)  First ape ever seen using medicinal plant to treat wound  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 1m 58s | After this orangutan sustained a gnarly facial wound, he did something kind of human-like. (1m 58s)  Total Eclipse in the Heart of Texas Hill Country  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 6m 41s | People from all over the country converge on a small Texas town to see a total solar eclipse. (6m 41s)  New map of the universe hints that dark energy may be evolving  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 3m | Dark energy fundamentally shapes our universe and what astronomers know about it might be wrong. (3m)  Are winters getting less snowy?  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 4m 49s | It's not just your imagination, winters across the U.S. are changing. (4m 49s)  How America watched the solar eclipse  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 2m 13s | Millions witnessed the Moon cover the Sun on April 8, some viewers sent us their videos. (2m 13s)  How to watch the eclipse without burning your eyes  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 1m 59s | A total solar eclipse is coming. If you want to check it out, you need eye protection. (1m 59s)  Rare stellar explosion will ignite a \\\"new star\\\"  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 1m 17s | Sometime between now and September a star will explode. (1m 17s)  The discovery of worlds beyond our solar system  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 1m 39s | How did we discover exoplanets? (1m 39s)  The force that makes up more than half of the universe  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 1m 40s | Dark Energy was first discovered in 1998, and scientists do not fully understand it. (1m 40s)  How parrots swing like monkeys  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 | 1m 36s | Like monkeys, parrots are also able to travel by suspending their body weight. (1m 36s)  Who is the Mystery Man Buried Under Notre Dame?  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 Ep18 | 3m | Can scientists identify the man buried inside a mysterious coffin found under Notre Dame? (3m)  Lost Tombs of Notre Dame Preview  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Preview: S51 Ep18 | 30s | Mysterious bodies are found under one of the world's most famous cathedrals. (30s)  Building Stuff: Change It! Preview  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Preview: S51 Ep17 | 30s | From electric flight to artificial noses, engineers are finding new ways to preserve our planet. (30s)  Building Stuff: Reach It! Preview  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Preview: S51 Ep16 | 30s | Humans are born to roam. See how engineers are inventing new ways to explore and extend our range. (30s)  Creating a Robotic Double Dutch Machine  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 Ep15 | 5m 8s | Blending innovation and culture, engineers bring a robotic Double Dutch machine to life. (5m 8s)  Building Stuff: Boost It! Preview  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Preview: S51 Ep15 | 30s | Is engineering humanity's superpower? See how we can amplify our natural abilities in amazing ways. (30s)  The Most Baffling Idea in Physics, Explained  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 Ep14 | 3m 33s | Quantum entanglement defies our everyday understanding of reality. (3m 33s)  How Atomic Clocks Keep Perfect Time  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 Ep14 | 2m 15s | Atomic clocks use quantum physics and the resonant frequency of atoms, like cesium, to define time. (2m 15s)  Decoding the Universe: Quantum Preview  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Preview: S51 Ep14 | 30s | Dive into the universe at the tiniest - and weirdest - of scales. (30s)  Solar System: Wandering Worlds Preview  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Preview: S51 Ep13 | 30s | Meet the surprising, oddball worlds moving around our solar system. (30s)  Could Mars Have a Ring Around It One Day?  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 Ep13 | 2m 16s | The moon Phobos has a mysterious origin but a certain expiration date. (2m 16s)  Cameras Capture Earthbound Meteorite  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 Ep13 | 1m 39s | Some large meteorites survive their descent through our atmosphere and land on Earth. (1m 39s)  Why Do Comets Have Tails?  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 Ep12 | 55s | As comets cross the invisible boundary known as the ice line, their ice starts turning into gas. (55s)  This Moon May Have the Ingredients for Life  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 Ep12 | 2m 14s | The ocean beneath Europa's icy shell might be an ideal environment for life. (2m 14s)  Solar System: Icy Worlds Preview  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Preview: S51 Ep12 | 30s | Visit strange, frozen worlds to discover the bizarre ice that forms beyond Earth. (30s)  This Tiny Moon Is a Volcanic Powerhouse  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 Ep11 | 2m 45s | Io's intense volcanic activity defies all expectations. (2m 45s)  Solar System: Volcano Worlds Preview  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Preview: S51 Ep11 | 30s | Discover the powerful volcanic eruptions that have shaped worlds across our solar system. (30s)  Enceladus: A Frozen Moon With Explosive Eruptions  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 Ep11 | 1m 56s | Enceladus' small size and icy surface is no limitation to its extreme volcanism. (1m 56s)  Could This Icy Moon's Ocean Support Life?  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 Ep11 | 1m 21s | Hydrothermal vents in Enceladus' ocean may hold the promise of life. (1m 21s)  Why is Haumea Shaped Like an Egg?  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 Ep10 | 2m 30s | Most objects with a radius over 200 miles are spherical, but Haumea is an exception. (2m 30s)  Solar System: Strange Worlds Preview  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Preview: S51 Ep10 | 30s | What are the weirdest worlds in our solar system, and how did they come to be? (30s)  How a Walnut-Shaped Moon Help Shape Saturn's Rings  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 Ep10 | 2m 35s | For millions of years, a tiny moon has made a significant impact on the structure of Saturn's rings. (2m 35s)  Venus: The Planet With Battery Acid Clouds  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 Ep9 | 3m 27s | This is what it would be like to walk on the surface of Venus. (3m 27s)  How the Martian Atmosphere Helped Nasa's Rovers Restore Energy  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 Ep9 | 2m 59s | Martian dust devils may have helped NASA's rovers restore power during mission. (2m 59s)  Solar System: Storm Worlds Preview  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Preview: S51 Ep9 | 30s | Discover the dramatic forces creating spectacular weather on neighboring planets and moons. (30s)  How Vera Rubin broke barriers in astronomy  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 Ep8 | 4m 4s | Vera Rubin's work provided convincing evidence for a mysterious substance, dark matter. (4m 4s)  The Deepest Underground Lab in the U.S.  Video hasClosed CaptionsCC  Clip: S51 Ep8 | 1m 44s | A team of researchers hunt for dark matter deep underground in the Black Hills of South Dakota. (1m 44s)  Providing Support for PBS.org  Capturing the splendor of the natural world, from the African plains to the Antarctic ice.  Take a journey through the history of life on Earth.  Support for PBS provided by:  National Corporate funding for NOVA is provided byCarlisle CompaniesandViking Cruises. Major funding for NOVA is provided by the NOVA Science Trust and PBS viewers.  Copyright \\u00a92026Public Broadcasting Service (PBS), all rights reserved. PBS is a 501(c)(3) not-for-profit organization.  New to PBS?Create an account  or  By creating an account, you acknowledge that PBS may share your information with our member stations and our respective service providers, and that you have read and understand thePrivacy PolicyandTerms of Use.  Are you sure you want to remove null from My List?\"}"